%N A392307 Number of composite numbers c such that c * sigma_n(c) == 2 (mod phi(c)).
%C A392307 The congruence in some sense characterizes the primes: all primes satisfy it automatically; and for any n, there are finitely many composites that satisfy it.
%C A392307 4 and 6 satisfy the congruence for any choice of n, so a(n)>=2.
%C A392307 Equivalently, counts the number of primes p such that (p-1) | (2^(n+2)+2); see A392306 for discussion.
%H A392307 A. Dujella and F. Luca, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1017/S1446788712000614">On a variation of a congruence of Subbarao</a>, Journal of the Australian Mathematical Society 93 (2012), 85-90.
%H A392307 S. Gong and Scott Duke Kominers, <a href="https://math.colgate.edu/~integers/k26/k26.Abstract.html">On congruence conditions for primality</a>, INTEGERS, 10 (2010), 313-317. [Note: Some elements missing from the table in this reference; corrected in "A flanking pattern" reference below.]
%H A392307 Scott Duke Kominers, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.18424">A flanking pattern in a sum-of-divisors congruence</a>, arXiv:2512.18424 [math.NT], 2025.
%H A392307 P. Lescot, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/3619591">A characterisation of prime numbers</a>, The Mathematical Gazette, 80 (1996), 400-401.
%H A392307 M. V. Subbarao, <a href="https://projecteuclid.org/journals/pacific-journal-of-mathematics/volume-52/issue-1/On-two-congruences-for-primality/pjm/1102912230.full">On two congruences for primality</a>, Pacific Journal of Mathematics, 52 (1974), 261-268.
%o A392307 (PARI) a(n) = my(nb=0, N=2^(n+2)+2); forprime(p=2, N+1, if (!(N % (p-1)), nb++)); nb; \\ _Michel Marcus_, Jan 08 2026
